column2: The name of the relevant Experiment (this value is user created at acquisition time)
The name of the relevant Cage
The name of the relevant Subject ID (this value is user created at acquisition time)
The name of the relevant Batch
The name of the relevant Phase (this value is user created at acquisition time)
The name of the relevant Sample
Represents the time at which the experiment began (as expressed in the time zone in which the experiment was created).
Represents time elapsed since the start of the experiment.
The total distance that the subject has traveled. This variable defines the subject's location as the centroid (center of mass) of the subject.
The total distance that the subject has traveled in one dimension (X-Axis). This variable defines the subject's location as the centroid (center of mass) of the subject.
The total distance that the subject has traveled in one dimension (Y-Axis). This variable defines the subject's location as the centroid (center of mass) of the subject.
A count of sensor changes (beam breaks).
Number of beam breaks while animal is ambulating. Does not include stereotypy behavior.
The length of time that the subject spent at rest.  A resting period is defined as a period of inactivity greater than or equal to 1 second.
The total number of resting periods.  A resting period is defined as a period of inactivity greater than or equal to 1 second.
The length of time that the subject spent in activity. Activity is defined as a period in which ambulation or stereotypy occurred.
The total number of locomotor episodes.  Episodes are separated by rest periods of at least 1 second.
The length of time that the subject spent in ambulatory activity. Ambulatory activity is defined as a period in which ambulation occurred.
Cumulative average over the course of the sample based on the varying trajectories of an animal's ambulatory displacements.
The total number of ambulatory episodes. Episodes are separated by rest periods of at least 1 second.

The total amount of time that stereotypic behavior is exhibited. A break in stereotypy of 1 second or more is required to separate one stereotypic episode from the next.  If the animal breaks the same beam (or set of beams) repeatedly then the monitor considers that the animal is exhibiting stereotypy. This typically happens during grooming or head bobbing.

This corresponds to the number of times that stereotypic behavior was observed in the animal. A break in stereotypy of 1 second or more is required to separate one stereotypic episode from the next.  If the animal breaks the same beam (or set of beams) repeatedly then the monitor considers that the animal is exhibiting stereotypy. This typically happens during grooming or head bobbing.

The number of beam breaks due to stereotypic activity. If the animal breaks the same beam (or set of beams) repeatedly then the monitor considers that the animal is exhibiting stereotypy. This typically happens during grooming or head bobbing.

Number of beam breaks that occur during a period of stereotypic activity. If the animal breaks the same beam (or set of beams) repeatedly then the monitor considers that the animal is exhibiting stereotypy. This typically happens during grooming or head bobbing.
This is incremented by 1 each time the animal rears.  The animal must go below the level of the vertical sensor for at least 1 second before the next rearing can be registered.
Time accumulated by the animal when breaking beams in the vertical layer.
Counts the number of clockwise revolutions that the subject travels in an open field.
Counts the number of counter-clockwise revolutions that the subject travels in an open field.
The mean of the average velocities for each ambulatory episode.
The highest value of the mean velocities for each ambulatory episode.
The median of velocities for each ambulatory episode.
Indicates the status of the light during a sample (on or off).
Indicates whether the fan was ever 'off' during a sample.
